Class HalfwayListCollector<T,A>

g41.si2022.util.collector.HalfwayListCollector<T,A>
Type Parameters:

All Implemented Interfaces:
Collector<T,List<A>,List<A>>
public abstract class HalfwayListCollector<T,A> extends Object implements Collector<T,List<A>,List<A>>
HalfwayListCollector.

A HalfwayListCollector is a concurrent Collector that has most methods implemented to handle List.
This way, we can avoid implementing them every time we need a Collector to transform data into a List.

A Collector can be used to transform a data type T into a List of A.

To do this, this class needs the method Collector.accumulator() to be implemented.

Practical Example:
If we have a java.util.HashMap<String, String> and we need a java.util.List<String> that contains all the values of the map, we can use a HalfwayListCollector<Hashmap<String, String>, String>.
The method Collector.accumulator() could be something like this:
public BiConsumer<List<String>, Map<String, String>> accumulator() {
  return (list, mapEntry) -> list.add(mapEntry.getValue());
}
